Clematis pitcheri is a flowering vine native to the southeastern United States. 
It is typically found growing in wooded areas and along stream banks. 
The flowers of Clematis pitcheri are pale blue to purplish in color and are shaped like bells. 
The leaves are dark green and glossy, with a somewhat leathery texture. 
The vine can grow up to 10 feet in length and is capable of climbing up trees or other supports. 
Clematis pitcheri is often grown as an ornamental plant in gardens due to its attractive foliage and flowers. 
In nature, it serves as an important source of food and habitat for a variety of insects and small mammals.
